  "prompt": "What can cause astigmatism?",
  "response": "Astigmatism is an optical condition characterized by an irregular curvature of the cornea or lens of the eye, which leads to blurred or distorted vision. Several factors can contribute to the development of astigmatism, including:\n\n1. **Genetics**: Astigmatism often runs in families, suggesting a hereditary component.\n\n2. **Corneal Shape**: The most common cause of astigmatism is an irregularly shaped cornea. Instead of being spherical, the cornea may be more oval or misshapen, causing light to focus on multiple points in the eye rather than a single point on the retina.\n\n3. **Lens Shape**: In some cases, the lens inside the eye can also be irregularly shaped, contributing to astigmatism.\n\n4. **Eye Injuries or Surgeries**: Trauma to the eye or certain types of refractive surgeries may result in astigmatism due to changes in the structure of the eye.\n\n5. **Keratoconus**: This is a progressive eye disease where the cornea thins and bulges, becoming cone-shaped, which can lead to significant astigmatism.\n\n6. **Pterygium**: A pterygium is a growth of fleshy tissue on the conjunctiva that can affect the shape of the cornea and lead to astigmatism.\n\n7. **Other Eye Conditions**: Conditions such as anisometropia (different refractive power in the two eyes) can also be associated with astigmatism.\n\n8. **Age-related Changes**: As people age, the lens of the eye can change shape or lose flexibility, potentially leading to astigmatism.\n\nIt is essential to consult an eye care professional for proper diagnosis and management if you suspect you have astigmatism or are experiencing vision problems.",
